                <head>64. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On June 20, 1968, Assistant Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_LJM1"
                        >Leddy</persName> and Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DK1">Duda</persName>
                    exchanged letters that made U.S. annuitants living in Czechoslovakia eligible
                    for Social Security and other benefit payments. <persName corresp="#p_LJM1"
                        >Leddy</persName> also informed <persName corresp="#p_DK1">Duda</persName>
                    that the United States was considering liberalization of its trade controls as
                    applied to Czechoslovakia and would be submitting new proposals on the gold
                    issue. The Assistant Secretary handed the Ambassador a note outlining U.S.
                    plans. The text with commentary was transmitted in telegram 188016 to Prague,
                    June 21. (Department of State, Central Files, POL CZECH–US)</p>
            </div>
